answer.commentary_en:
So the intended meaning is: “I do not ask you for any wage for my call; rather, whoever wishes may take a path to his Lord through obedience.” Some exegetes also mentioned another estimation meaning: “I do not ask you for any wage for my call; rather, if you take the path of Islam and acts of obedience, then that is my wage in what I will receive from Allah in reward for that.”
Likewise, Allah’s statement in the second verse: {Say: I do not ask you any wage for it except love due to kinship.}
Here, some may think the Prophet ﷺ asks his people for a wage for his call—namely, that they love him—but that is not the case. If he were asking them for affection for the sake of the call, that would indeed be a kind of wage. Rather, the meaning is: “I ask you no wage whatsoever for conveying; I only ask you for affection because of the kinship between me and you.” Their affection for him due to his kinship is what their chivalry and honorable conduct would require. This too is a disconnected exception. Even asking them to show him affection was for the benefit of his call, peace and blessings be upon him. Ibn ‘Ashur said in At-Tahrir wa At-Tanwir: he only asked for affection because treating him with affection helps spread the call of Islam; their hostility softens, they cease resisting him, and he becomes able to convey the call more perfectly—so this affection becomes a religious aim with no personal worldly benefit for the Prophet ﷺ.

answer.ayah_ar:
وَجَاءَهُ قَومُهُ يُهْرَعُونَ إِلَيْهِ وَمِن قَبْلُ كانوا يَعْمَلُونَ السَّيِّئَاتِ قَالَ يا قوم هؤلاء بناتى
هُنَّ أَطْهَرُ لَكُم فَاتَّقُوا اللَّهَ وَلا تُخزون فى ضيفى أَلَيسَ مِنكُم رَجُلٌ رَشِيدٌ)
]78 : هود[

وَالَّذِينَ سَعَوا فى آياتِنَا مُعاجِزِينَ أُولئِكَ لَهُم عَذابٌ مِن رِجْزٍ أَلِيمٌ * وَيَرَى الَّذِينَ
أوتُوا العِلمَ الَّذِي أُنزِلَ إِلَيكَ مِن رَبِّكَ هُوَ الحَقَّ وَيَهدى إلى صراط العزيز الحميد)
]6 : سبأ[
